ce:section.ce:para:
Herein, o-phenylenediamine (OPD) was used as precursor via a facile microwave-assisted method for preparing dual-emission CDs (d-CDs). The d-CDs were applied to fabricate the ratiometric fluorescent sensor with opposite response for detecting Cu2+ (
Scheme 1
). The nanosensor possessed excellent selectivity and sensitivity in detecting Cu2+ with wide linear range and low LOD, which could be ascribe to the self-calibrations of ratiometric sensor and the special responding mechanism between the d-CDs and Cu2+. Moreover, the sensor exhibited satisfied results for detecting Cu2+ in spiked food samples, indicating its promising potentials for practical applications.

To investigate the chemical groups of the d-CDs, FTIR spectrum was recorded and presented in Fig. 1C. The characteristic broad band from 3100 to 3700 cm−1 could provide convincing evidence for the presence of oxygen and amino functional groups on the d-CDs surfaces [28]. The absorption peaks at ∼1631 and 1515 cm−1 accounted for the C=N and N–H stretching vibration [15,23]. Moreover, the peak at ∼1389 cm−1 was aromatic C=C stretching frequency [28]. The other two peaks at 1193 and 1110 cm−1 were associated with the C–O and C–N stretching frequencies [23]. These results may be due to the d-CDs possessed abundant active groups containing N (e.g. –NH2) on their surfaces. To further investigate the functional groups of the d-CDs, XPS survey spectrum of the d-CDs was recorded. As showed in Fig. 1D, three prominent peaks at 284.37, 399.07, and 532.11 eV respectively ascribed to the characteristic peaks of C1s, N1s, and O1s. From high-resolution spectra of C1s (

                           Fig. S1A

                        ), three peaks at 284.62, 285.29 and 286.16 eV were observed, which were respectively attributed to C–C/-CH, C–N and C=O. The high-resolution spectra of O1s (

                           Fig. S1B

                        ) displayed two main peaks at 532.26 and 533.07 eV, which were contributed to C=O and C–OH/C–O–C. Moreover, the spectra of N1s (

                           Fig. S1C

                        ) de-convoluted into three main peaks at 398.71, 399.19, and 399.98 eV were respectively corresponded to pyridine N, amino groups N and pyrrolic N. These nitrogenous functional groups may be formed during the formation of the d-CDs through polymerization of OPD [27]. The results of XPS analyses were coincident with those FITR analyses, which revealed abundant active groups containing N (e.g. –NH2) and aromatic structures existed on the d-CDs surface, thus could provide potential recognition sites for coordinating Cu2+. Together with the analysis results of UV–vis spectrum, it could confirm that the d-CDs possessed abundant residual groups of OPD, which may be due to the incomplete carbonization of OPD in the condensation reaction of the d-CDs [15,20].
